#rstats #dplyr tip: don't do

case_when( <expr> ~ blah,
                      !<expr> ~ notblah)

It evals expr **two entirely separate times**. Use ifelse() or if you REALLY MUST use case_when (not sure why...) do

case_when( <expr> ~ blah,
                      TRUE ~ notblah)

TIL (from Adv R) a neat way to standardize or do something to a column of a data frame: 
f <-  function(x) x / mean(x)
mtcars[] <- lapply(mtcars, f)

an alternative to purrr::modify(mtcars,  f) or dplyr::mutate_all(mtcars, f). #rstats

<<
Just as there are three basic ways to use a for loop, there are three basic ways to use lapply():

lapply(xs, function(x) {})
lapply(seq_along(xs), function(i) {})
lapply(names(xs), function(nm) {})
